The arcade game received positive reviews upon release.<ref name="CU">{{cite magazine |last1=Lacy |first1=Eugene |title=Xevious |magazine=[[Commodore User]] |date=20 December 1986 |issue=40 (January 1987) |pages=26–7 |url=https://archive.org/details/commodore-user-magazine-40/page/n25/mode/2up}}</ref> ''[[Computer & Video Games]]'' magazine praised the game's thrilling action and impressive graphics, recommending it to players fond of titles such as ''[[Zaxxon]]'' and ''[[Scramble (video game)|Scramble]]'',<ref name="CVG">{{cite magazine |title=Aliens Take a Tumble: Xevious |magazine=[[Computer + Video Games]] |issue=20 (June 1983) |date=16 May 1983 |page=31 |url=https://www.solvalou.com/arcade/reviews/177/495 |access-date=9 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916021921/https://www.solvalou.com/arcade/reviews/177/495 |archive-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> while ''[[Electronic Games]]'' found that the realistic graphics and intense action made ''Xevious'' an easy recommendation to fans of the genre. ''Joystik'' stated that the game was superior to titles ''Zaxxon'' and ''[[Tron (video game)|Tron]]'', specifically in its graphics and gameplay.<ref name="Joystik">{{cite news |title=Xevious |url=https://archive.org/details/joystik_magazine-1983-10/page/n23?q=xevious |access-date=9 November 2019 |agency=Joystik |volume=2 |edition=Special |date=October 1983 |pages=40–43}}</ref>

''Amusement Life'' praised its detailed backgrounds, fast-paced gameplay and sense of mystery, labeling it a masterpiece and one of the best games of 1983.<ref>{{cite news |title=EXCITING NEW VIDEO GAME - ギャラガ |url=https://archive.org/details/amusement-life-magazine-14/page/n22?q=%E3%82%AE%E3%83%A3%E3%83%A9%E3%82%AC |access-date=22 September 2019 |agency=Amusement Life |issue=14 |date=February 1982 |page=21 |language=ja}}</ref> In 1998, ''[[Allgame]]'' called it one of the more "polite" shoot'em ups for its detailed visuals, challenge and unique enemy designs, finding it to have a "charm" unmatched by other games of the genre.<ref name="Allgame"/>

Home versions of ''Xevious'' received praise for their faithfulness to the original. ''[[Your Sinclair]]'' commended the ZX Spectrum version's accurate conversion of the arcade original, while also praising its fast-paced gameplay and "enthralling" experience.<ref name="YS">{{cite news |last1=Berkmann |first1=Marcus |title=Xevious Review |url=http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/xevious.htm |access-date=9 November 2019 |agency=[[Your Sinclair]] |issue=14 |date=February 1987 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312081839/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/xevious.htm |archive-date=12 March 2016}}</ref> ''Nintendojo'' greatly praised the ''Classic NES Series'' version for its gameplay and multiplayer mode, favorably comparing it to games such as ''[[Gradius]]''.<ref name="Nintendojo"/> They felt that its responsive controls and "chaotic" difficulty made it one of the best titles released under the label.<ref name="Nintendojo"/>

Some home releases were met with a more mixed reception for their overall quality and lack of bonus features. Reviewing the Nintendo Entertainment System release, German publication ''Power Play'' found the game to be "too old", suggesting that readers instead try out titles such as ''[[Gradius]]''.<ref name="Power Play">{{cite news |author1=MH |title=Xevious |url=http://www.kultpower.de/archiv/heft_powerplay_1989-06_seite56 |access-date=9 November 2019 |agency=Power Play |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208102948/http://www.kultpower.de/archiv/heft_powerplay_1989-06_seite56 |archive-date=8 December 2015 |page=57 |language=de}}</ref> They also disliked the game's lack of power-ups and for areas being too long.<ref name="Power Play"/> ''GameSpot'' applauded the Xbox 360 digital version's emulation quality and usage of online leaderboards,<ref name="GameSpot">{{cite web |last1=Gerstmann |first1=Jeff |title=Xevious Review |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/xevious-review/1900-6171444/ |website=GameSpot |access-date=23 May 2007}}</ref> but ''IGN'' and ''GameSpot'' both disliked the lack of improvements made over previous home releases and bonus content.<ref name="IGN"/><ref name="GameSpot"/>

Retrospectively, ''Xevious'' has been seen as the "father" of vertical-scrolling shooters and one of the most influential and important games of the genre. In 1995, [[Flux (magazine)|Flux]] magazine rated the game 88th on their Top 100 Video Games writing: "Xevious ushered in a new age of scrolling overhead shooters in 1984 with its detailed graphics, multi-level targets and catchy theme music."<ref>{{Cite journal |date=April 1995 |title=Top 100 Video Games |url=https://archive.org/details/flux-issue-4/page/n31/mode/2up |journal=Flux |publisher=Harris Publications |issue=4 |pages=32}}</ref> In 1996, ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' ranked it at #90 in their "Top 100 Games of All Time", praising its art direction, intense gameplay and layer of strategy.<ref name="NGen21">{{cite magazine |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=21  |date=September 1996 |page=39}}</ref>
''[[Gamest]]'' magazine ranked it the second greatest arcade game of all time in 1997 based on reader vote, applauding its pre-rendered visuals, addictive nature and historical significance.<ref name="Gamest1997">{{cite book |title=Reader's Choice of Best Game |publisher=Gamest |isbn=9784881994290 |page=48}}</ref>

Japanese publication ''Yuge'' found the Famicom home port to be one of the system's best and most memorable titles for its faithful portrayal of the original.<ref name="usedgame07"/> ''Hardcore Gaming 101'' applauded the game for setting up the template for future games of the genre, namely ''[[TwinBee]]'', ''[[RayForce]]'' and ''[[Raiden DX]]''.<ref name="hardcore"/> They also praised the game's detailed graphics, difficulty and impressive enemy intelligence for the time.<ref name="hardcore"/> ''IGN'' labeled it the 9th greatest [[Atari 7800]] game of all time for its gameplay and overall quality.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Buchanan |first1=Levi |title=Top 10 Atari 7800 Games |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/05/09/top-10-atari-7800-games |publisher=[[IGN]] |access-date=9 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010231611/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/05/09/top-10-atari-7800-games |archive-date=10 October 2018 |date=9 May 2008}}</ref>

===Commercial performance===
''Xevious'' was an unprecedented success for Namco in Japan. In its first few weeks on the market, it recorded record-breaking sales figures that hadn't been seen since ''[[Space Invaders]]'' in 1978.<ref>{{cite book |title=ARCADE GAMERS White Paper Vol . 1 |date=2010 |publisher=Media Pal |isbn=978-4896101089 |page=10}}</ref> It was the top-grossing [[table arcade cabinet]] on Japan's ''Game Machine'' arcade charts in November 1983.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - テーブル型TVゲーム機 (Table Videos) |magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]] |issue=213 |publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press]] |date=1 June 1983 |page=29 |lang=ja |url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19831115p.pdf#page=15}}</ref> In North American arcades, it was a more moderate success, reaching number-four on the ''[[Play Meter]]'' arcade charts in July 1983.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Top 15 Arcade Games |magazine=Video Games |date=September 1983 |volume=1 |issue=12 |page=82 |url=https://archive.org/details/Video_Games_Volume_1_Number_12_1983-09_Pumpkin_Press_US/page/n81/mode/1up}}</ref> Atari sold 5,295 [[arcade cabinet]]s in the US by the end of 1983, earning about $11.1 million (equivalent to ${{formatprice|{{inflation|US|11,100,000|1983}}}} in {{inflation/year|US}}){{inflation/fn|US}} in US cabinet sales revenue.<ref name="atari_production">{{cite web |title=Atari Production Numbers Memo |url=http://www.atarigames.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47:atari-production-numbers-memo&catid=5:atari-inter-office-memos&Itemid=5 |publisher=[[Atari Games]] |access-date=18 March 2012 |date=4 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120084806/http://www.atarigames.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47%3Aatari-production-numbers-memo&catid=5%3Aatari-inter-office-memos&Itemid=5 |archive-date=20 January 2013}}</ref>

The [[Famicom]] version became the console's first [[killer app]] with over 1.26 million copies sold in Japan,<ref>{{cite web |title=Japan Platinum Game Chart |url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-JPPlatinum.shtml |website=The Magic Box |access-date=23 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801030711/http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-JPPlatinum.shtml |archive-date=1 August 2019}}</ref> jumping system sales by nearly 2 million units.<ref name="usedgame07">{{Cite magazine |author=遠藤昭宏 |title=ユーゲーが贈るファミコン名作ソフト100選 アクション部門 |date=June 2003 |magazine=ユーゲー |publisher=キルタイムコミュニケーション |issue=7 |pages=6–12}}</ref> The game's immense popularity led to high score tournaments being set up across the country, alongside the creation of [[strategy guide]]books that documented much of its secrets and hidden items.<ref>{{cite news |title=ゼビウス |url=https://archive.org/details/amusement-life-magazine-11/page/n22?q=%E3%82%BC%E3%83%93%E3%82%A6%E3%82%B9 |access-date=9 November 2019 |agency=Amusement Life |issue=11 |date=October 1983 |pages=21–22}}</ref> The NES version went on to sell {{nowrap|1.5 million}} [[game cartridges]] worldwide.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sheff |first1=David |title=[[Game Over: How Nintendo Conquered the World]] |year=1994 |orig-year=1993 |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |isbn=978-0-307-80074-9 |chapter=Inside the Mother Brain |page=72 |chapter-url=https://file1.largepdf.com/file/2020/04/08/Game_Over_-_David_Sheff.pdf#page=72 |quote=Namco sold 1.5 million copies of a game called "Xevious". A new Namco building was nicknamed the Xevious Building because the game had paid for its construction costs. |access-date=2021-01-02 |archive-date=2021-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210102104823/https://file1.largepdf.com/file/2020/04/08/Game_Over_-_David_Sheff.pdf#page=72 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Legacy==
{{see also|List of Xevious media}}

''[[Bubble Bobble]]'' creator [[Fukio Mitsuji]] and ''[[Rez (video game)|Rez]]'' producer [[Tetsuya Mizuguchi]] cite ''Xevious'' as having a profound influence on their careers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fukio "MTJ" Mitsuji - 1988 Developer Interview |url=http://shmuplations.com/bubblebobble/ |access-date=8 November 2019 |agency=BEEP! |year=1988 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008222008/http://shmuplations.com/bubblebobble/ |archive-date=8 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2016-03-17-recollections-of-rez |title=Recollections of Rez |first=Brendan |last=Sinclair |date=2016-03-17 |access-date=2016-03-17 |work=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322185636/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2016-03-17-recollections-of-rez |archive-date=2016-03-22}}</ref>

''Xevious'' is credited as one of the first video games to have a [[boss fight]],<ref name="Gamest1997"/><ref name="hardcore"/> [[pre-rendered]] graphics<ref name="NGen21"/> and a storyline.<ref name="Gamest1997"/> In 1985, Roger C. Sharpe of ''[[Play Meter]]'' magazine stated that the "dimensionalized, overhead perspective of modern, detailed graphics was launched with ''Xevious''."<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Sharpe |first1=Roger C. |title=Critic's Corner |magazine=[[Play Meter]] |date=July 15, 1985 |volume=11 |issue=13 |pages=25–31 |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/b/b3/PlayMeter_US_Volume_11_No._13.pdf#page=23}}</ref>

===Sequels and spin-offs===
''[[Super Xevious]]'' was released in 1984.  The difficulty was increased to appeal to more advanced players, alongside new enemy types and characters that reset the player's score when shot.<ref name="hardcore"/> A similarly titled game was released in 1986 for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Family Computer]], ''[[Super Xevious: GAMP no Nazo]]'', which intermixed puzzle elements with the standard ''Xevious'' gameplay.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Savorelli |first1=Carlo |title=Super Xevious: GAMP no Nazo |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/super-xevious-gamp-no-nazo/ |website=Hardcore Gaming 101 |access-date=10 December 2013}}</ref> An arcade version of this game was also released, known as ''Vs. Super Xevious'', running on the [[Nintendo Vs.]] arcade system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vs. Super Xevious |url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=13050 |website=Killer List of Video Games |access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> An arcade spin-off title starring one of the enemies from ''Xevious'', ''[[Grobda]]'', was released in 1984.<ref>{{cite web |title=Grobda |url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=8015 |website=Killer List of Video Games |access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref>

Two games for the MSX2 and PC-Engine were released in 1988 and 1990 respectively - ''Xevious Fardraut Saga'' and ''Xevious Fardraut Densetsu'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Savorelli |first1=Carlo |title=Xevious: Fardraut Saga (PC-Engine) |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/xevious-fardraut-saga-pc-engine/ |website=Harccore Gaming 101 |access-date=10 December 2014}}</ref> both of which include a remade port of the original alongside a brand-new story mode with new enemies, boss fights and power-up items.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Savorelli |first1=Carlo |title=Xevious: Fardraut Saga |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/xevious-fardraut-saga/ |website=Harccore Gaming 101 |access-date=10 December 2013}}</ref> A 3D rail-shooter spin-off, ''[[Solvalou]]'', was published in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |title=Solvalou |url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=9618 |website=Killer List of Video Games |access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> In 1995, two arcade sequels were released - ''[[Namco Classic Collection Vol. 1|Xevious Arrangement]]'', a remake of the original with two-player co-op,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Savorelli |first1=Carlo |title=Xevious Arrangement |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/xevious-arrangement/ |website=Hardcore Gaming 101 |access-date=10 December 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Xevious 3D/G]]'', a 3D game with 2D gameplay - both of these titles were soon released in 1997 for the PlayStation, compiled into ''Xevious 3D/G+'', alongside the original ''Xevious'' and ''Super Xevious''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=IGN Staff |title=Xevious 3D/G+ |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/1997/06/12/xevious-3dg |website=IGN |date=11 June 1997}}</ref> A final follow-up was released in 2009, ''[[Xevious Resurrection]]'', exclusively as part of the compilation title ''[[Namco Museum#Namco Museum Essentials|Namco Museum Essentials]]'', which includes two-player simultaneous co-op alongside a number of other features.<ref>{{cite web |author=Spencer |title=New Xevious Bundled With PSN Namco Museum |url=https://www.siliconera.com/2009/01/28/new-xevious-bundled-with-psn-namco-museum/ |website=Siliconera |date=28 January 2009 |access-date=28 January 2009}}</ref>

===Music and books===
In 1991, a three-part ''Xevious'' novel was published, titled ''Fardraut'' - the books documented the lore of the ''Xevious'' video game series, including its characters, backstory and events. The books would be republished fifteen years later in 2005.<ref name="hardcore"/> A 2002 CGI film adaptation was released in Japan, produced during a collaboration between Namco and Japanese company Groove Corporation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Namco Announces Xevious CG Movie |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2002/02/08/namco-announces-xevious-cg-movie |website=IGN |date=8 February 2002 |access-date=8 February 2002}}</ref>

A ''Xevious''-themed soundtrack album was produced by [[Haruomi Hosono]] of [[Yellow Magic Orchestra]] in 1984, titled ''Video Game Music''. Compiled with music from other Namco video games, such as ''[[Mappy]]'' and ''[[Pole Position]]'', it is credited as the first video game soundtrack album.<ref name="Gamest1991">{{cite book |title=The Most Loved Games!! Best 30 Selected By Readers |publisher=Gamest |page=7 |edition=6th}}</ref> ''Xevious'' would also spawn the first gameplay recording for a video game<ref name="Gamest1991"/> and the first television commercial for an arcade game.<ref name="museum">{{cite news |url=http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=10505 |title=Xevious |work=The International Arcade Museum |access-date=2012-11-20}}</ref> Music from the game was used during the video game-themed television series ''[[Starcade]]''.<ref name="museum"/>

